{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019c5JnKZy5t7PE9rzEvSAum","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Architecture\n     2→\n     3→## Overview\n     4→\n     5→RNG Utopia is structured as a pnpm monorepo containing the platform shell, individual game applications, and shared packages. The frontend is built with React, TypeScript, and Vite. The backend consists of Solana programs for on-chain game logic and a lightweight off-chain service layer for real-time coordination.\n     6→\n     7→Scope alignment note: V1 direction is defined in `../../docs/SCOPE.md`. Architectural details for token, referral/rakeback, and other expansion mechanics are post-V1 unless explicitly called out as V1.\n     8→\n     9→**Core Principles:**\n    10→- On-chain programs are authoritative for all financial settlement\n    11→- Off-chain services handle UX optimization and real-time coordination\n    12→- All randomness is provably fair and independently verifiable\n    13→- Idempotent operations prevent double-settlement and replay attacks\n    14→\n    15→---\n    16→\n    17→## Monorepo Structure\n    18→\n    19→```\n    20→rng-utopia/\n    21→├── apps/\n    22→│   ├── platform/           # Main shell - routing, layout, shared state\n    23→│   ├── close-call/         # Pari-mutuel BTC candle prediction\n    24→│   ├── crash-simulator/    # P2P crash game - last to cash out wins\n    25→│   ├── lord-of-rngs/       # Winner-takes-all jackpot wheel\n    26→│   ├── coinflip/           # 1v1 50/50 coin flip\n    27→│   ├── game-of-trades/     # Multiplayer trading competition\n    28→│   ├── slots-utopia/       # P2P slots (loyalty-gated)\n    29→│   ├── chart-the-course/   # Price trajectory prediction\n    30→│   └── tug-of-earn/        # Team-based tap battle\n    31→├── packages/\n    32→│   ├── ui/                 # Design system components\n    33→│   ├── game-engine/        # Client-side game state (UI only, not authoritative)\n    34→│   ├── fairness/           # Provable fairness verification utilities\n    35→│   ├── wallet/             # Privy integration and transaction helpers\n    36→│   ├── vrf/                # VRF client integration\n    37→│   ├── price-feeds/        # Real-time price data integration\n    38→│   └── config/             # Shared configuration (eslint, tsconfig, etc.)\n    39→├── solana/                 # Solana programs (Anchor workspace)\n    40→│   ├── programs/coinflip/  # Coinflip game logic, settlement\n    41→│   ├── programs/platform/  # Platform settings, player profiles\n    42→│   └── shared/             # Common types, fee constants (lib crate)\n    43→├── crates/                 # Shared Rust libraries\n    44→│   ├── payout-math/        # Payout calculation invariants\n    45→│   └── fairness-core/      # Commit-reveal and verification logic\n    46→├── services/\n    47→│   ├── coordinator/        # Real-time game coordination (Node.js/Rust)\n    48→│   └── indexer/            # On-chain event indexing service\n    49→├── package.json\n    50→├── pnpm-workspace.yaml\n    51→├── turbo.json\n    52→└── README.md\n    53→```\n    54→\n    55→---\n    56→\n    57→## Custody Model\n    58→\n    59→**Architecture Decision: Non-Custodial (Recommended)**\n    60→\n    61→Players always move funds on-chain into per-round pool escrow PDAs. The platform never holds user balances in off-chain ledgers.\n    62→\n    63→### Why Non-Custodial\n    64→\n    65→| Aspect | Non-Custodial | Custodial |\n    66→|--------|---------------|-----------|\n    67→| Trust model | Trustless - funds in escrow PDAs | Requires trust in platform |\n    68→| Compliance | Simpler - not a money transmitter | Requires banking-grade ledgering |\n    69→| Transparency | Full on-chain auditability | Requires external audits |\n    70→| UX friction | More transactions | Faster micro-bets |\n    71→\n    72→### Fund Flow\n    73→\n    74→```\n    75→Entry:\n    76→1. Player clicks to join a round\n    77→2. Frontend constructs entry transaction:\n    78→   - Transfer SOL to round-specific escrow PDA\n    79→   - Register player in pool state\n    80→3. Transaction signed by player's wallet\n    81→4. Pool-manager program accepts entry atomically\n    82→5. Player's entry is now escrowed on-chain\n    83→\n    84→Payout:\n    85→1. Round resolves (outcome determined)\n    86→2. Settlement transaction executed:\n    87→   - Pool-manager calculates payouts\n    88→   - Fees transferred to treasury PDA\n    89→   - Winnings transferred directly to winner wallets\n    90→3. All transfers atomic in single transaction\n    91→```\n    92→\n    93→### UX Optimization (Without Custodial Balances)\n    94→\n    95→To reduce transaction friction while remaining non-custodial:\n    96→\n    97→- **Batched entries:** Allow multiple bets in single transaction where applicable\n    98→- **Session keys:** Privy session authority for faster signing (user-controlled delegation)\n    99→- **Transaction sponsorship:** Platform pays gas for small bets (relayer pattern)\n   100→- **Pre-approved limits:** User pre-authorizes max bet amounts per session\n   101→\n   102→---\n   103→\n   104→## Source of Truth\n   105→\n   106→| Data Type | Source of Truth | Why |\n   107→|-----------|-----------------|-----|\n   108→| User funds | On-chain (wallet + escrow PDAs) | Trustless custody |\n   109→| Pool state | On-chain (pool-manager PDAs) | Financial settlement |\n   110→| Round outcomes | On-chain (settlement tx) | Auditability |\n   111→| Fee collection | On-chain (treasury PDA) | Transparency |\n   112→| Game state (live) | Coordination server | Low latency |\n   113→| User profiles | Off-chain DB | Non-financial |\n   114→| Leaderboards | Indexer DB (derived) | Recomputable from chain |\n   115→| Round history | Indexer DB (derived) | Recomputable from chain |\n   116→\n   117→**Rule:** Anything involving money settlement must be on-chain. Derived views can be off-chain but must be recomputable from on-chain data.\n   118→\n   119→---\n   120→\n   121→## Provable Fairness Standard\n   122→\n   123→All games must use one of two approved randomness patterns. This is enforced via `packages/fairness` and `crates/fairness-core`.\n   124→\n   125→### Pattern 1: Commit-Reveal + Future Chain Seed\n   126→\n   127→**Use for:** Games with predetermined outcomes (Crash)\n   128→\n   129→```\n   130→Before betting opens:\n   131→1. Server generates serverSeed (random 32 bytes)\n   132→2. Server publishes commitment: commit = sha256(serverSeed)\n   133→3. Commitment stored on-chain or published via indexer\n   134→\n   135→During betting:\n   136→4. Players place bets (server cannot change serverSeed)\n   137→\n   138→At round start:\n   139→5. Capture publicSeed from future Solana slot blockhash\n   140→   (slot must be after betting closes)\n   141→\n   142→After round:\n   143→6. Server reveals serverSeed\n   144→7. Outcome computed: HMAC-SHA256(serverSeed, publicSeed || roundId || gameId)\n   145→8. Anyone can verify: sha256(serverSeed) == published commit\n   146→\n   147→Why this works:\n   148→- Server commits before knowing publicSeed → can't manipulate outcome\n   149→- publicSeed from future block → server can't predict it during betting\n   150→- Commitment public → server can't change serverSeed after betting\n   151→```\n   152→\n   153→**Implementation:**\n   154→```rust\n   155→// crates/fairness-core\n   156→pub fn compute_crash_point(\n   157→    server_seed: &[u8; 32],\n   158→    public_seed: &[u8; 32],\n   159→    round_id: u64,\n   160→    game_id: &str,\n   161→) -> f64 {\n   162→    let input = [public_seed, &round_id.to_le_bytes(), game_id.as_bytes()].concat();\n   163→    let hash = hmac_sha256(server_seed, &input);\n   164→    hash_to_crash_point(&hash)\n   165→}\n   166→\n   167→pub fn verify_commitment(server_seed: &[u8; 32], commitment: &[u8; 32]) -> bool {\n   168→    sha256(server_seed) == *commitment\n   169→}\n   170→```\n   171→\n   172→### Pattern 2: On-Chain VRF\n   173→\n   174→**Use for:** Games requiring on-chain winner selection (Lord of the RNGs, Coinflip)\n   175→\n   176→```\n   177→1. Round enters resolution phase\n   178→2. Program requests VRF (Switchboard/Orao)\n   179→3. VRF provider fulfills with proof\n   180→4. Program verifies proof and stores result\n   181→5. Winner selected using VRF output\n   182→6. Result permanently on-chain with proof\n   183→```\n   184→\n   185→**VRF Provider Requirements:**\n   186→- On-chain verifiability\n   187→- Low latency (sub-second for real-time games)\n   188→- Cost efficiency at scale\n   189→- Providers under evaluation: Switchboard VRF, Orao Network\n   190→\n   191→### Per-Game Fairness Requirements\n   192→\n   193→Each game spec must document:\n   194→- Which randomness pattern it uses\n   195→- When the outcome becomes determined\n   196→- What gets stored on-chain\n   197→- How a third party verifies the result\n   198→- Link to verification API/tool\n   199→\n   200→---"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01PRSLefhQeBwpvqapfE6EQp","session_id":"e8e7bcc0-e29f-4246-996e-49dc6d7211e9","uuid":"b19f6a9e-0662-4a95-aef6-e8437d8f935c"}
